{"id":"2201.07461","submitter":"Lidia Stocker","authors":"Lidia Stocker, Stefan H. Sack, Michael S. Ferguson and Oded Zilberberg","title":"Entanglement based observables for quantum impurities","comments":"6 pages, 4 figures, comments are welcome","journal-ref":"Phys. Rev. Research 4, 043177 (2022)","doi":"10.1103/PhysRevResearch.4.043177","report-no":null,"categories":"cond-mat.mes-hall cond-mat.str-el quant-ph","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  Quantum impurities exhibit fascinating many-body phenomena when the small\ninteracting impurity changes the physics of a large noninteracting environment.\nThe characterisation of such strongly correlated non-perturbative effects is\nparticularly challenging due to the infinite size of the environment, and the\ninability of local correlators to capture the build-up of long-ranged\nentanglement in the system. Here, we harness an entanglement-based observable -\nthe purity of the impurity - as a witness for the formation of strong\ncorrelations. We showcase the utility of our scheme by exactly solving the open\nKondo box model in the small box limit, and thus describe all-electronic\ndot-cavity devices. Specifically, we conclusively characterise the\nmetal-to-insulator phase transition in the system and identify how the\n(conducting) dot-lead Kondo singlet is quenched by an (insulating)\nintra-impurity singlet formation. Furthermore, we propose an experimentally\nfeasible tomography protocol for the measurement of the purity, which motivates\nthe observation of impurity physics through their entanglement build-up.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Wed, 19 Jan 2022 08:08:35 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Fri, 13 Jan 2023 16:23:10 GMT"}],"update_date":"2023-01-16"}
