{"id":"2202.00474","submitter":"V. A. Golovko","authors":"V.A. Golovko","title":"Is the electron magnetic moment unique?","comments":"A paragraph concerning the probabilistic interpretation of the wave\n  function is added in the concluding section","journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"physics.gen-ph","license":"http://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/4.0/","abstract":"  There exist two methods for finding the magnetic moment of the electron. In\nthe first of them employed in quantum electrodynamics, one calculates the\nenergy of the electron placed in a constant magnetic field, the extra energy\ndue to the field being proportional to the magnetic moment. It is also possible\nto use the second method proceeding from the fact that the asymptotic form of\nthe vector potential at infinity is proportional to the magnetic moment. If the\nelectron were point-like, both the methods would yield identical results. In\nthe present paper is studied the magnetic field created by the electron in\nhydrogen-like ions, which enables one to find the electron magnetic moment by\nthe second method. The electron magnetic moment in this case proves to be\ndifferent in different states of the electron in the Coulomb field of the ions\nand, moreover, is distinct from the magnetic moment calculated by the first\nmethod. The results of the paper show that the electron is not small and is\ndeformable under action of external fields.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Wed, 19 Jan 2022 08:31:54 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Wed, 2 Feb 2022 09:03:40 GMT"},{"version":"v3","created":"Wed, 23 Feb 2022 10:39:24 GMT"},{"version":"v4","created":"Mon, 6 Jun 2022 11:27:43 GMT"},{"version":"v5","created":"Wed, 10 Aug 2022 17:59:37 GMT"}],"update_date":"2022-08-11"}
